    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1963-05-22T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1963-05-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="342"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d342">
                <head>342. Memorandum From the President’s Special Assistant for National Security
                    Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_BMG2" type="from">Bundy</persName>) to the <gloss
                        type="to">Members of the Standing Group of the National Security
                        Council</gloss>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d342fn0">Source: Kennedy Library, National
                        Security Files, Countries Series, Cuba, General, 5/16-5/31/63. Secret. This
                        memorandum was briefly discussed at the 6th meeting of the Standing Group,
                        May 21. It was circulated with general agreement to the assignments.
                        (Summary Record of 6th <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> StandingGroup,
                        May 21; ibid., Meetings and Memoranda Series, Standing Group Meeting,
                        5/21/63)</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1963-05-22">May 22, 1963</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Committee Responsibilities in Cuban Affairs</item>
                </list>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>The Coordinator of Cuban Affairs, acting as Chairman of the
                        Interdepartmental Committee on Cuba, is responsible for the coordination of
                        day-to-day actions. Examples of such problems are: efforts to reduce Cuban
                        Free World shipping, problems of refugees, problems of countering Cuban
                        subversion, and supervision of ongoing propaganda and information efforts.
                        This list is illustrative and not exhaustive. On covert matters, the
                        Coordinator reports to the Special Group (<gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                            >NSC</gloss> 5412).</item>
                    <pb facs="0848" n="820" xml:id="pg_820"/>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>The Standing Group is responsible for the development of contingency plans
                        and the assessment of long-range policy objectives and means for meeting
                        them.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>The Special Group (<gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> 5412) is
                        responsible for covert activities, with appropriate liaison to the other two
                        committees.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BMG2">
                            <hi rend="strong">McGeorge Bundy</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <note n="1" xml:id="d342fn1">Printed from a copy that bears this typed
                            signature.</note>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
